00:45:10,474 --> 00:45:12,999
We could make it
our wishing well.

638
00:45:13,110 --> 00:45:15,374
And we could have...

639
00:45:15,479 --> 00:45:17,777
a rustic bridge...

640
00:45:17,881 --> 00:45:19,940
with a stream flowing
beneath it,

641
00:45:20,050 --> 00:45:23,451
not too deep
because of the children.

642
00:45:23,520 --> 00:45:26,512
<i>And we could have gnomes,</i>
<i>mushrooms.</i>

643
00:45:40,804 --> 00:45:43,796
<i>Billy!</i>
<i>Are you feeling all right ?

644
00:45:43,907 --> 00:45:46,171
Of course, darling. Why ?

645
00:45:46,276 --> 00:45:48,176
Well, look where your hand is.

646
00:45:48,278 --> 00:45:52,009
Oh. But I want to touch you.

647
00:45:52,116 --> 00:45:55,483
Well, it seems indecent somehow.

648
00:45:57,020 --> 00:46:00,786
[ Sighs ] You know you're
making me ill, don't you ?

649
00:46:00,858 --> 00:46:03,986
Oh, poor pet.
Why am I making you ill ?

650
00:46:04,061 --> 00:46:08,430
Well, surely you've heard of,
well, of repressions.

651
00:46:09,933 --> 00:46:13,369
The nervous reactions
of a man who's not--

652
00:46:13,470 --> 00:46:15,938
I know what you mean, pet,
but we must be patient.

653
00:46:16,039 --> 00:46:18,837
We must.
I mean, we'd only regret it.

654
00:46:18,909 --> 00:46:21,275
-Well,just have one more energy tablet.
-No, thank you.

655
00:46:21,378 --> 00:46:25,439
- I'm going to have an orange.
-" I'm going to have--"
You and your bloody oranges !

656
00:46:30,053 --> 00:46:33,545
[ Stammering ]
I'm sorry, darling.

657
00:46:33,824 --> 00:46:35,985
l-I've had a terrible morning.

658
00:46:41,064 --> 00:46:43,032
- I've come about a ring.
- Oh, yes.

659
00:46:43,100 --> 00:46:45,227
An engagement ring
brought in for alterations.

660
00:46:45,335 --> 00:46:48,498
- Oh, I see. What name is it, madam ?
- It should be under Fisher.

661
00:46:48,572 --> 00:46:52,064
- Fisher. Just a moment.
- If he gave you my name,
it would be Corrigan.

662
00:46:52,142 --> 00:46:55,578
Corrigan. Just a moment.
Fisher. Corrigan. Fisher. Corrigan.

663
00:46:55,846 --> 00:46:58,110
- Got a Farmer.
- No, no, Fisher. Fisher.

664
00:46:58,215 --> 00:47:00,115
- Hey, what was that ?
- Where ?

665
00:47:00,217 --> 00:47:04,051
- That at the bottom.
- That's Cor-Corcoran.
That's a cuckoo clock.

666
00:47:04,121 --> 00:47:07,249
- When did it come in ?
- Wednesday, I think. So he said.

667
00:47:07,357 --> 00:47:10,383
- Uh, darling.
- Mmm ?

668
00:47:10,494 --> 00:47:12,519
Are you still coming
for your tea tomorrow ?

669
00:47:12,596 --> 00:47:14,928
Oh, of course.

670
00:47:15,032 --> 00:47:16,932
Oh, well, if you are,

671
00:47:17,034 --> 00:47:20,401
there are some things we've got
to get cleared up and implemented.

672
00:47:20,504 --> 00:47:22,563
What things ?

673
00:47:22,639 --> 00:47:25,938
You know I've got a fairly vivid
imagination, don't you, darling ?

674
00:47:26,043 --> 00:47:29,479
Well, you have to have if you're
going to be a scriptwriter, don't you ?

675
00:47:29,580 --> 00:47:32,310
Right. Well,
being a scriptwriter,

676
00:47:32,416 --> 00:47:34,543
I'm perhaps at times
a bit inclined...

677
00:47:34,618 --> 00:47:37,610
to let my imagination
run away with me,

678
00:47:37,888 --> 00:47:40,288
as you know.

679
00:47:40,390 --> 00:47:42,290
You don't mean
you've been telling me lies.

680
00:47:42,392 --> 00:47:46,522
Not lies, exactly.
But I suppose I've been, you know,

681
00:47:46,630 --> 00:47:50,088
exaggerating some things a bit,
being a scriptwriter.

682
00:47:50,167 --> 00:47:52,601
For instance, there's
that business about me father--

683
00:47:52,870 --> 00:47:55,361
him getting danger money
on a petrol tanker.

684
00:47:55,472 --> 00:47:59,169
- He's not on a petrol tanker ?
- He wasn't even in the navy.

685
00:47:59,276 --> 00:48:02,268
- What was he, then ?
- He was a conscientious object--

686
00:48:02,379 --> 00:48:06,247
No, he wasn't anything. He wasn't fit.
He has trouble with his knees.

687
00:48:06,316 --> 00:48:08,284
Oh.

688
00:48:09,553 --> 00:48:11,953
How many other lies
have you been telling me ?

689
00:48:12,022 --> 00:48:15,048
-Uh, me sister.
-Don't tell me you haven't got a sister.

690
00:48:15,158 --> 00:48:17,626
Well, I did have,
but she's dead.

691
00:48:17,895 --> 00:48:22,525
If you're still coming for you tea
tomorrow, they never talk about her.

692
00:48:22,633 --> 00:48:25,227
<i>[ Car Passes By ]

693
00:48:25,335 --> 00:48:30,068
Come on. I'm just not good enough
for you, you know, Barbara.

694
00:48:30,173 --> 00:48:33,165
You ought to give me
that engagement ring back.

695
00:48:33,277 --> 00:48:35,177
I'll understand.

696
00:48:37,381 --> 00:48:39,474
- I forgive you, pet.
- Oh.

697
00:48:39,583 --> 00:48:41,483
But promise me one thing.

698
00:48:41,585 --> 00:48:43,712
- That I'll never lie to you again ?
- Mm-hmm.

699
00:48:43,987 --> 00:48:46,581
I'll never lie to you again.
Never. I promise.

700
00:48:49,393 --> 00:48:51,327
[ Sighs, Chuckles ]

701
00:48:51,395 --> 00:48:53,454
Billy, are we going
dancing tonight ?

702
00:48:53,530 --> 00:48:57,432
<i>Billy, are we going</i>
<i>dancing tonight, to the Roxy?</i>

703
00:48:57,534 --> 00:49:01,698
Don't say anything.
There's Arthur's mother.

704
00:49:01,972 --> 00:49:03,701
- <i>[ Chuckles ]
- Good afternoon.

705
00:49:03,974 --> 00:49:07,535
Good afternoon, Mrs. Crabtree. I don't
think you've met my sister Sheila.

706
00:49:07,644 --> 00:49:11,444
- <i>Sheila, Mrs. Crabtree.</i>
- Don't try and be clever with me.

707
00:49:11,548 --> 00:49:14,312
I happen to know Barbara
very well indeed !

708
00:49:14,384 --> 00:49:17,751
[ Chuckles ]
Well,

709
00:49:18,021 --> 00:49:21,548
I'm catching a bus, actually.

710
00:49:23,093 --> 00:49:24,685
But, Billy !

711
00:49:26,730 --> 00:49:28,630
I should watch him.

712
00:49:30,434 --> 00:49:34,461
[ Announcer] Jane Wildeblood coming
to the last fence for a clear round.

713
00:49:34,538 --> 00:49:37,735
No, I'm afraid she's--
I'm afraid she's down there.

714
00:49:38,008 --> 00:49:41,136
- <i>She was completely unseated.</i>
- They build them fences too high.

715
00:49:41,211 --> 00:49:43,679
[ Chuckles ]
They tumble down.

716
00:49:43,780 --> 00:49:48,046
<i>[ TVAnnouncer ]
<i>Of course she will be penalized,</i>
<i>and that does spoil her chances.</i>

717
00:49:48,151 --> 00:49:50,051
Is that our Billy ?

718
00:49:50,153 --> 00:49:52,678
His old raincoat's been
in the bathroom all morning.

719
00:49:52,789 --> 00:49:56,418
And if it isn't our Billy,
where's his old raincoat been, then ?

720
00:49:56,526 --> 00:50:00,121
Don't you be so cheeky.
And what time do you call this ?

721
00:50:00,230 --> 00:50:04,098
27 minutes,
13 seconds past 2:00.

722
00:50:04,201 --> 00:50:07,193
- I've had a very eventful morning.
- Don't pick !

723
00:50:07,270 --> 00:50:09,534
You seem to think I've nothin'
else better to do but cook.

724
00:50:09,606 --> 00:50:13,542
Well, you get no dinner.
I've finished cookin' for one day.

725
00:50:13,610 --> 00:50:17,808
You ought to start
comin' home for dinnertime,
instead of gabbin' about town.

726
00:50:18,081 --> 00:50:21,050
- Good afternoon, Father.
- I've not sat down all morning.

727
00:50:21,151 --> 00:50:25,087
If I'm not sick-- I'm doin' this
for you. Do you realize that ?

728
00:50:25,155 --> 00:50:28,181
You've got Barbara
comin' for tea tomorrow,
but you won't do anything, will ya ?

729
00:50:28,258 --> 00:50:30,488
- <i>You've no consideration.</i>
- <i>[ Doorbell Rings ]

730
00:50:30,594 --> 00:50:32,562
<i>She sounds like such</i>
<i>a nice girl, this Barbara.</i>

731
00:50:32,629 --> 00:50:34,597
<i>[ Father ]
<i>Go answer that bell. Go on.</i>

732
00:50:34,698 --> 00:50:38,600
You're idle and scruffy,
and you have no manners.

733
00:50:38,702 --> 00:50:41,466
- What are manners ?
- Talk some sense, man.

734
00:50:41,571 --> 00:50:45,063
If that's what they learnt
when he went to grammar school,
thank God I'm bloody ignorant.

735
00:50:45,142 --> 00:50:47,542
- A confession !
- Don't be cheeky.

736
00:50:47,644 --> 00:50:50,112
<i>[ Doorbell Rings ]

737
00:50:51,681 --> 00:50:55,481
- You !
- Hello, Rita. Just a minute.

738
00:50:55,585 --> 00:50:57,746
Who is it, Billy ?

739
00:50:57,854 --> 00:51:00,049
Just a minute.

740
00:51:00,123 --> 00:51:03,251
[ Mumbling ]

741
00:51:03,326 --> 00:51:07,057
Yes, you rotten, lying, cross-eyed git !
You're nothing else !

742
00:51:07,130 --> 00:51:10,793
Hello, Rita. Sorry I can't ask you in.
We're having our chimney swept.

743
00:51:11,068 --> 00:51:13,468
They'll be having you swept
before I finish.

744
00:51:13,570 --> 00:51:16,801
It might just interest you to know
I have been down to that jewelers,

745
00:51:17,074 --> 00:51:19,804
and they've never heard of you,
never mind that flamin' ring.

746
00:51:19,876 --> 00:51:21,867
- You must have gone to the wrong shop.
- No, I didn't !

747
00:51:22,145 --> 00:51:24,545
I went to the right shop.
Hendersons in Bridge Street.

748
00:51:24,648 --> 00:51:27,082
That's funny.
Did you see Mr. McMichael ?

749
00:51:27,150 --> 00:51:29,311
I saw the fellow
behind the counter !

750
00:51:29,419 --> 00:51:32,252
Well, you should have asked
Mr. McMichael in the workshop.

751
00:51:32,322 --> 00:51:35,120
He's my godfather.
He's doing it privately.

752
00:51:35,192 --> 00:51:37,251
You are rotten to me, Billy.

753
00:51:37,327 --> 00:51:40,319
It's true. Ask me dad
if you don't believe me.

754
00:51:40,397 --> 00:51:42,365
That's me Uncle Ernest.

755
00:51:42,466 --> 00:51:44,696
<i>My dear old Uncle Ernest.</i>

756
00:51:44,801 --> 00:51:49,170
Oh, I don't know where I am with you,
Billy. We're supposed to be engaged !

757
00:51:49,272 --> 00:51:52,264
- You once said you didn't
want to marry me.
- I did not !

758
00:51:52,342 --> 00:51:55,675
I said I weren't gonna live
in a rotten cottage in Devon,
so don't come that one with me.

759
00:51:55,779 --> 00:51:58,339
I want that ring back,
and I want it tonight !

760
00:51:58,415 --> 00:52:02,146
That's just it. I've got to stay in
to play Monopoly with Uncle Ernest.

761
00:52:02,252 --> 00:52:05,187
Oh, Monopoly ! I'll tell you
what you're doing tonight.

762
00:52:05,288 --> 00:52:07,483
You're taking me dancing,
to the Roxy.

763
00:52:07,557 --> 00:52:10,492
I'll see you outside at 7:00.
And don't you be late, right ?

764
00:52:12,496 --> 00:52:16,159
Barbara-- I mean, Rita !
Oh, hell.

765
00:52:17,634 --> 00:52:19,625
- Afternoon.
- Afternoon.

766
00:52:22,873 --> 00:52:25,398
<i>[ Sportscaster On TV]</i>
<i>Meanwhile in this open race--</i>

767
00:52:25,509 --> 00:52:29,343
Hey, come in here, you.
Who's she supposed to be ?

768
00:52:29,412 --> 00:52:32,870
- Oh,just a friend.
- That's not the one that's
coming for tea tomorrow, is it ?

769
00:52:33,150 --> 00:52:35,584
- No, that's Barbara.
- Well, who's this one, then ?

770
00:52:35,685 --> 00:52:38,210
Just a friend.
She was just passing.

771
00:52:38,321 --> 00:52:41,688
She's gone to see her Uncle Ernest.
He lives up on that new estate.

772
00:52:41,758 --> 00:52:44,249
They're all
new houses up there.

773
00:52:44,361 --> 00:52:47,524
- I thought you were thinking
of getting engaged.
- Some has two bedrooms--

774
00:52:47,597 --> 00:52:50,157
- Yes, but--
- You can't carry on like this.

775
00:52:50,233 --> 00:52:52,963
- messin' about
with one lass after another.
- I realize that.

776
00:52:53,236 --> 00:52:55,898
Well, if you are gonna get
engaged, why not wait a bit ?

777
00:52:56,173 --> 00:52:59,336
Some has bathrooms upstairs,
and some has bathrooms downstairs.

778
00:52:59,409 --> 00:53:02,207
I don't believe in interfering,
but if you're gonna get engaged,
well, bloody get engaged.

779
00:53:02,312 --> 00:53:04,303
If you're not,
well, don't bloody bother.

780
00:53:04,414 --> 00:53:06,882
<i>But don't come to me and say</i>
<i>that I tried to stop you.</i>

781
00:53:06,983 --> 00:53:09,918
It's not that simple, Dad. I haven't
really decided what I want to do yet.

782
00:53:10,187 --> 00:53:12,781
Well, you couldn't do any worse
than me and your mother.

783
00:53:12,889 --> 00:53:15,790
When we started, we hadn't
two ha'pennies to rub together.

784
00:53:15,892 --> 00:53:18,884
I told her, I said,
"You don't get married till you're 21."

785
00:53:18,995 --> 00:53:21,828
- Well, we've managed.
- It's not a question of managing, Dad.

786
00:53:21,932 --> 00:53:24,400
It's just that I haven't
made me mind up yet.

787
00:53:24,467 --> 00:53:27,527
You want to make your mind up
before she makes it up for you.

788
00:53:27,637 --> 00:53:30,367
- If I go to London--
- When your mom was 21, I said,

789
00:53:30,440 --> 00:53:32,772
- " You can do as you like."
-Just a minute, Grandma.

790
00:53:32,876 --> 00:53:35,538
- " Don't come running to me
if you can't manage."
-Just a minute !

791
00:53:35,612 --> 00:53:38,206
- " You've got to make--"
- For God's sake, belt up !

792
00:53:38,281 --> 00:53:42,217
You, what ? What did you say ?
Say that again !

793
00:53:42,285 --> 00:53:45,254
- I'm only remarking--
- Talk bloody properly
when you talk to me !

794
00:53:45,355 --> 00:53:48,654
What did you say to your grandmother ?
Ignorant, that's what you are !

795
00:53:48,758 --> 00:53:51,454
Hey, look out.
That's shirt's clean.

796
00:53:51,561 --> 00:53:54,496
I'll clean shirt him, answering
his grandmother back like that !

797
00:53:54,598 --> 00:53:58,227
- Leave him alone.
- Him and his fountain pens
and bloody suede shoes.

798
00:53:58,335 --> 00:54:00,963
- If he wants to go to London,
he can bloody well go.
- Oh, but he's not.

799
00:54:01,238 --> 00:54:03,934
- I'm finished with him. He can go.
- But he's not.

800
00:54:04,007 --> 00:54:07,443
- He can pack his things and get going !
- I'm telling you, he's not.

801
00:54:07,510 --> 00:54:10,536
- I can explain all of this.
- Ever since he started work.

802
00:54:10,614 --> 00:54:13,742
Grumbling about this. If it isn't
his boiled egg, it's something else.

803
00:54:13,850 --> 00:54:16,785
- Oh, shut up.
- So what do you do ?
Buy him special corn flakes.

804
00:54:16,886 --> 00:54:20,253
- What if I do ?
- And why ? Because there's
a submarine in the package.

805
00:54:20,323 --> 00:54:22,951
- He wants putting away.
- Now, you just listen to me.

806
00:54:23,026 --> 00:54:25,790
- He's not old enough to go to London--
- Not old enough ?

807
00:54:25,895 --> 00:54:28,796
He's old enough to get
into the bloody army.

808
00:54:28,898 --> 00:54:31,867
- You want to get into
the bloody army as well.
- Oh, for heaven's sake !

809
00:54:31,968 --> 00:54:36,769
<i>Hold your noise, Geoffrey.</i>
<i>I can't stand it anymore.</i>
<i>I've been cooking in here--</i>

810
00:54:36,840 --> 00:54:40,435
<i>[ Geoffrey ] Well, every day</i>
<i>it's the same. It gets on my nerves.</i>

811
00:54:40,510 --> 00:54:42,944
- <i>[ Arguing Continues ]
- Mom !

812
00:54:43,013 --> 00:54:47,473
Mom, i-it's Gran.
It think she's had another of her dos.

813
00:54:47,584 --> 00:54:50,018
Now look what you've done.

814
00:54:50,287 --> 00:54:52,551
Get her tablets, Geoffrey.

815
00:54:52,656 --> 00:54:56,786
Hey, get them tablets out
of the dressing table drawer.
Go on, go on, move !

816
00:54:56,893 --> 00:55:00,829
- [ Indistinct ]
- [ Muttering ]

817
00:55:00,897 --> 00:55:04,389
We must get her onto the couch.
She'll be all right there.

818
00:55:04,501 --> 00:55:06,935
You'll be all right, love.
You'll be all right.

819
00:55:17,747 --> 00:55:21,945
Oh, come on, get out of there.
I can't wait all day for you.

820
00:55:26,623 --> 00:55:29,956
<i>[ Mother ] Come on, Geoffrey!</i>
<i>Haven't you found them yet ?

821
00:55:30,026 --> 00:55:32,927
<i>Oh, come on, Geoffrey!</i>
<i>Hurry up!</i>

822
00:56:26,683 --> 00:56:29,584
- You weigh a ton.
- Feathers.

823
00:56:29,652 --> 00:56:32,849
She wants to burn some feathers.
Never mind pills.

824
00:56:32,922 --> 00:56:36,187
Here you are. That's it.
Put it in your mouth.

825
00:56:36,426 --> 00:56:38,485
Come on. Have a sip.

826
00:56:38,595 --> 00:56:41,894
- Is she all right ?
- As all right as she'll ever be.

827
00:56:41,998 --> 00:56:44,762
All right.
I'll be off, then.

828
00:56:46,202 --> 00:56:49,569
-Where's he going ?
-Oh, we've more to worry about than him.

829
00:56:49,672 --> 00:56:53,665
- Now you all right, love ?
- [ Sighs, Chuckles ]

830
00:56:59,916 --> 00:57:02,885
<i>[ Riveter Pounding ]

831
00:57:10,059 --> 00:57:13,051
<i>[ Crowd Cheering ]

832
00:57:25,141 --> 00:57:27,735
[ Cheering Stops ]

833
00:57:27,811 --> 00:57:30,109
We have fought.

834
00:57:30,180 --> 00:57:32,842
We have fought long and hard.

835
00:57:32,949 --> 00:57:37,477
Now at last,
our struggle has been rewarded.

836
00:57:37,587 --> 00:57:39,885
Italy is within our grasp !

837
00:57:39,989 --> 00:57:43,481
I offer you nothing but liberty,
fraternity and equality !

838
00:57:43,593 --> 00:57:46,619
<i>[ Crowd Cheering ]

839
00:57:49,098 --> 00:57:51,623
Come on !

840
00:57:53,236 --> 00:57:56,171
[ Billy On Speaker]
We will rebuild !

841
00:57:56,272 --> 00:57:59,503
Cannon and mortar
have devastated...

842
00:57:59,609 --> 00:58:03,238
our drab and shoddy streets.

843
00:58:03,513 --> 00:58:07,472
<i>But this I pledge.</i>

844
00:58:07,584 --> 00:58:09,984
<i>Battalions of craftsmen...</i>

845
00:58:10,053 --> 00:58:12,988
<i>will change the face</i>
<i>of our city.</i>

846
00:58:13,056 --> 00:58:16,150
We will build towers !

847
00:58:16,259 --> 00:58:19,092
Towers !

848
00:58:21,664 --> 00:58:24,497
- No less.
- [ Cheering Continues ]

849
00:58:31,875 --> 00:58:35,538
<i>[ Crowd Chanting ]
<i>Fisher! Fisher! Fisher!</i>

850
00:58:40,884 --> 00:58:43,216
<i>[ Rooster Crowing ]

851
00:58:56,633 --> 00:59:00,000
<i>[ Film Narrator ]
<i>Overshadowing all events is</i>
<i>the massacre at Bluebell Valley.</i>

852
00:59:00,103 --> 00:59:02,901
<i>And General Fisher makes</i>
<i>a personal pilgrimage...</i>

853
00:59:03,006 --> 00:59:06,066
<i>to the war-scarred fields</i>
<i>where he himself was wounded.</i>

854
00:59:06,175 --> 00:59:09,076
<i>Meanwhile, protests are pouring</i>
<i>into the United Nations...</i>

855
00:59:09,178 --> 00:59:12,579
<i>as once again a shadow falls</i>
<i>across the world.</i>

856
00:59:12,682 --> 00:59:15,082
<i>Truly, history</i>
<i>has been made again...</i>

857
00:59:15,184 --> 00:59:17,345
<i>and in violent fashion.</i>

858
00:59:19,756 --> 00:59:21,849
Now then, lad.

859
00:59:24,594 --> 00:59:26,892
Afternoon, Councilor.

860
00:59:26,996 --> 00:59:29,965
- Well, it's a grand day for it.
- Aye.

861
00:59:30,066 --> 00:59:32,057
Been watching football, eh ?

862
00:59:32,168 --> 00:59:34,830
I'm just bound for a walk
over the moor.

863
00:59:34,904 --> 00:59:37,600
What've you got there ?
The Crown Jewels ?

864
00:59:37,707 --> 00:59:39,971
No, gramophone records, LPs.

865
00:59:40,076 --> 00:59:43,273
There were naught like that
when I were a lad.

866
00:59:43,379 --> 00:59:47,873
No record players. We had to make
us own music if we wanted it.

867
00:59:47,951 --> 00:59:50,215
Male voice choir we used to have.

868
00:59:50,286 --> 00:59:52,220
Then there was Chapel Choir.

869
00:59:52,288 --> 00:59:57,248
There were two Chapel Choirs
because there was another
chapel down Moor Cross Road.

870
00:59:57,327 --> 01:00:01,229
Ah, but they're all comin' down,
all the old buildings.

871
01:00:01,297 --> 01:00:06,325
Trams, they've gone.
City center, that's all new.

872
01:00:06,603 --> 01:00:10,061
Aye, but you could get
a glass of beer, meat pie,

873
01:00:10,173 --> 01:00:13,142
cigarettes, matches and change
out of four pence.

874
01:00:13,242 --> 01:00:15,369
- Aye.
- Aye.

875
01:00:15,612 --> 01:00:18,342
Dost thou think
I could climb down yonder ?

876
01:00:18,615 --> 01:00:20,344
That would break your neck.

877
01:00:20,617 --> 01:00:23,313
Well, I'll have to manage
it, whether or not.

878
01:00:23,419 --> 01:00:26,183
I'm going down
to the police station.

879
01:00:26,289 --> 01:00:28,780
Wh-What are you
going there for ?

880
01:00:28,858 --> 01:00:33,227
- Well, we're pulling it down.
- That's not, is that ?

881
01:00:33,329 --> 01:00:37,629
Yeah, that.
All yon cottages and all are going.

882
01:00:37,734 --> 01:00:39,827
Well, I'll be on my way
now, Councilor.

883
01:00:39,936 --> 01:00:42,427
So, afternoon.

884
01:00:42,705 --> 01:00:44,639
Aye.

885
01:00:44,707 --> 01:00:46,800
I say.

886
01:00:49,646 --> 01:00:51,409
<i>Come here.</i>

887
01:00:53,650 --> 01:00:56,744
You're a right one
with them calendars, aren't you ?

888
01:00:56,819 --> 01:01:00,721
- [ Nervous Chuckle ]
- I'd have thought thee had
more sense than that, lad.

889
01:01:00,823 --> 01:01:04,281
So, you're planning
to go to London then, eh ?

890
01:01:04,394 --> 01:01:08,330
Aye. Just about through
with this place.

891
01:01:08,398 --> 01:01:10,332
How do you mean ?

892
01:01:10,400 --> 01:01:14,166
Why, it's neither muckling
nor mickling, is it ?

893
01:01:14,270 --> 01:01:17,330
Thou art taking a rise
out of me, young man ?

894
01:01:17,440 --> 01:01:19,237
No, sir !

895
01:01:19,342 --> 01:01:23,108
Well, then just talk as your father
and mother brought thee up to talk.

896
01:01:23,179 --> 01:01:26,273
I had no education.
I had to educate myself.

897
01:01:26,349 --> 01:01:29,147
But that's no reason to mock me.

898
01:01:29,218 --> 01:01:32,381
Now then, I don't know
what else to do yet.

899
01:01:32,488 --> 01:01:35,946
I haven't decided.
But listen.

900
01:01:36,025 --> 01:01:39,188
- <i>Can you take a bit of advice ?
- Yes, sir.

901
01:01:39,295 --> 01:01:42,264
Now, you're a young man.

902
01:01:42,365 --> 01:01:46,961
You've got a long way to go,
but you can't do it by yourself.

903
01:01:47,070 --> 01:01:49,766
<i>Now, think on.</i>

904
01:01:51,374 --> 01:01:53,467
Me grandma's poorly.

905
01:01:53,743 --> 01:01:57,509
Well, I'm glad to have had
the chance of a word with you.

906
01:01:59,048 --> 01:02:01,881
[ Coughing ]

907
01:02:02,985 --> 01:02:05,180
Now, think on.

908
01:03:06,415 --> 01:03:09,407
<i>[ Newspaper Salesman, Indistinct ]

909
01:03:13,222 --> 01:03:17,283
<i>[ Bell Tolling ]

910
01:03:17,393 --> 01:03:20,590
We'll be back in London in about three
hours, so I'll call you then.

911
01:03:20,863 --> 01:03:23,889
-Okay. Bye.
-They charged us for four single rooms !

912
01:03:23,966 --> 01:03:28,266
Phone calls to London,
London, Luton.

913
01:03:28,371 --> 01:03:30,862
- <i>Luton ?
- Excuse me.

914
01:03:30,940 --> 01:03:33,465
-Yeah ?
-Have you anything to do with Mr. Boon ?

915
01:03:33,576 --> 01:03:36,977
- Can I help you ?
- I was wondering if I could
have a word with him.

916
01:03:37,079 --> 01:03:39,980
- You want an appointment.
He's extremely busy.
- I have written-

917
01:03:40,082 --> 01:03:42,175
Somebody's had
26 other phone calls.

918
01:03:42,285 --> 01:03:44,253
- Do you know him ?
- I've never seen him.

919
01:03:44,320 --> 01:03:48,916
Don't turn him away, Bertie.
I've got three gross of these to unload.

920
01:03:48,991 --> 01:03:51,221
- What's your name, son ?
- I'm Billy Fisher.

921
01:03:51,294 --> 01:03:53,285
" To Billy."

922
01:03:53,396 --> 01:03:56,422
I haven't put " with love."
People might get the wrong idea.

923
01:03:56,499 --> 01:03:59,627
- Be seeing you.
- Uh, no.

924
01:03:59,902 --> 01:04:03,531
- <i>I sent you some of my scripts.</i>
- Scripts ?

925
01:04:03,639 --> 01:04:06,130
- You sent me some scripts ?
- Yes. You wrote me a letter.

926
01:04:06,209 --> 01:04:09,337
You said that I was to call
and see your manager.

927
01:04:09,445 --> 01:04:13,006
Oh, did you ?
And here you are, eh ?

928
01:04:13,115 --> 01:04:16,642
Well, so you want to be
a scriptwriter, eh, Billy ?

929
01:04:16,919 --> 01:04:19,285
Well, it's a great life.
It really is.

930
01:04:19,355 --> 01:04:21,880
How's it going ?
Have you sold any material ?

931
01:04:21,991 --> 01:04:26,121
Well, I was hoping that
you would be able to use me...

932
01:04:26,195 --> 01:04:28,356
in some way as a scriptwriter.

933
01:04:28,464 --> 01:04:31,490
Oh, oh, well,
that's just it, Billy.

934
01:04:31,601 --> 01:04:34,297
You see, I don't maintain
a personal script writer.

935
01:04:34,403 --> 01:04:37,133
I've got enough to do
supporting these layabouts here.

936
01:04:37,206 --> 01:04:40,403
'Course, I'm always in the market
for individual gags, you know.

937
01:04:40,509 --> 01:04:43,444
And I pay pro rata.
Are you ever up in London ?

938
01:04:43,512 --> 01:04:46,140
- Now and again.
- Well, I'll tell you what you do.

939
01:04:46,215 --> 01:04:49,582
You pop in and see me at the office.
We'll have a bit of a chat.

940
01:04:49,685 --> 01:04:53,314
Well, good luck then, Billy,
and keep writing, eh ?

941
01:04:55,024 --> 01:04:57,515
[ Indistinct Chattering ]

942
01:05:12,675 --> 01:05:15,405
[ Screaming ]

943
01:05:20,683 --> 01:05:23,311
[ Chattering ]

944
01:05:34,997 --> 01:05:38,023
- Has he stood you up, then ?
- Oh, get off your knees !

945
01:05:38,134 --> 01:05:40,728
Come with us. We'll take you home.
Won't we, Todd ?

946
01:05:41,003 --> 01:05:43,130
Yeah, we'll take you home.
Come on.

947
01:05:43,239 --> 01:05:45,503
- Come on.
- Right, then.

948
01:05:45,574 --> 01:05:48,737
- Here you are.
- Hey ! Not so free with the hands !

949
01:05:49,011 --> 01:05:51,741
<i>[ Motorcycles Revving ]

950
01:05:58,721 --> 01:06:01,622
[ Chattering Continues ]

951
01:06:08,431 --> 01:06:11,195
- <i>[ Applause ]
- Thanks, mate.

952
01:06:11,267 --> 01:06:14,703
<i>¤ ¤[ Swing ]

953
01:07:16,766 --> 01:07:18,825
- Hello, Liz.
- Hello, Billy.

954
01:07:19,101 --> 01:07:21,296
- I knew you were back.
- Oh, news travels fast.

955
01:07:21,404 --> 01:07:24,032
- Where have you been this time ?
- Here and there.

956
01:07:24,140 --> 01:07:26,165
- Up and down.
- 'Round and about.

957
01:07:26,275 --> 01:07:28,470
- Why didn't you ring me up ?
- I was going to.

958
01:07:28,544 --> 01:07:32,173
- Thank you very much.
- No, really I was going to.
I knew you'd be here tonight.

959
01:07:32,281 --> 01:07:36,308
So I am here, my dear.
Me and a few others.

960
01:07:38,788 --> 01:07:40,688
- <i>How's everything with you ?
- <i>Fine.</i>

961
01:07:40,790 --> 01:07:43,350
How's the script writing,
and how's that book coming along ?

962
01:07:43,459 --> 01:07:46,189
I finished it.
It's gonna be published next Christmas.

963
01:07:46,295 --> 01:07:48,786
Count five and tell the truth.

964
01:07:50,433 --> 01:07:52,765
Oh, well, I haven't
started writing it yet.

965
01:07:52,868 --> 01:07:55,530
- Oh, bad as ever.
- I've written some scripts.

966
01:07:55,638 --> 01:07:58,539
- Have you ? Honest ?
- I've been offered a job
in London, script writing.

967
01:07:58,641 --> 01:08:00,165
- No !
- It's for the comedian Danny Boon.

968
01:08:00,242 --> 01:08:02,176
Really ?
I met him this morning.

969
01:08:02,278 --> 01:08:05,213
He was opening the supermarket,
and he asked me to cut the tape.

970
01:08:05,314 --> 01:08:07,214
So I noticed in the paper.

971
01:08:07,316 --> 01:08:10,183
- Well, when're you going ?
- Oh, soon.

972
01:08:10,286 --> 01:08:13,722
- When's soon ?
- Well, as soon as I can manage.

973
01:08:13,823 --> 01:08:17,088
It's a bit vague.
Why don't you go now ?

974
01:08:17,193 --> 01:08:19,855
- Why, it's difficult.
- No, it's not. It's easy.

975
01:08:20,096 --> 01:08:22,860
You get on a train, and four hours
later, there you are in London.

976
01:08:23,132 --> 01:08:26,260
It's easy for you.
You've had the practice.

977
01:08:29,371 --> 01:08:31,771
Shall we go for a walk
or something ?

978
01:08:31,874 --> 01:08:34,240
- Soon.
- Thank you.

979
01:08:35,778 --> 01:08:40,340
¤ Kookie Twisterella
She hasn't got a fella ¤

980
01:08:40,416 --> 01:08:42,748
<i>¤ ¤[ Continues, Indistinct ]

981
01:08:42,852 --> 01:08:44,752
- Hey, " Twisterella."
- Eh ?

982
01:08:44,854 --> 01:08:47,755
- It's my song. Me and Arthur wrote it.
- Honestly ?

983
01:08:47,857 --> 01:08:50,189
Yeah, words and music
by Fisher and Crabtree.

984
01:08:50,292 --> 01:08:53,159
We gave it to them months ago.
The never said they were gonna
play it tonight.

985
01:08:53,229 --> 01:08:55,390
- Did you really write it ?
- Isn't it great ?

986
01:08:55,498 --> 01:08:57,466
